project.content: The Chicago-Tübingen Archaeological Project in Sam'al

context.displayPath: Projects/The Chicago-Tübingen Archaeological Project in Sam'al/Eastern Citadel/Area 2

description:
Topsoil with modern debris and bioturbation, as well as a possible dump pile from a previous excavation.
No IA pottery; 1 piece in this bunch seems to be very weird and is undetermined. "If this is topsoil it is really so clean." -Sebastiano

notes.content: We made two different pottery pails. Pottery pail #3 is specifically for what we think may be a dump pile from previous excavations in the NE corner of the square. Several centimeters down, there are a number of rocks, which may be part of the dump pit. Pottery pail #4 is for the topsoil of the rest of the square. We started excavating in the SW corner for pottery pail #4 because it's at the highest elevation. There is modern burnt trash in this area along the 46.0A/B Baulk.

notes.title: 08-07-17 (AMW)
notes.content: We continued removing soil from the area in the NE corner where we think might have been a dump pile. I became less convinced that the entire area was a dump pile, however. It seems that there was a small dump towards the middle of our NE section because the soil here was extremely loose. There was also modern metal here. In much of this area we have come down upon a number of rocks and detritus, including burnt bricks and bone. Three of the stones line up and may turn out to be a feature. We had to use hand picks around the rocks. In the center north and north parts of the rest of the topsoil removal (Pail #6), more scattered rocks were found probably related to the rocks found in the suspected dump area. This entire part of the trench will likely become the next locus. We will know tomorrow after we sweep the rocks and delineate them. Bone, lots of pottery, and modern trash such as glass and plastic were found in the rest of the area covered by Pail #6. We finished removing the first few centimeters of topsoil all over the trench and began another pass of about 7 cm starting in the SW corner. The area supervisor and the square supervisor looked at the foundations of the Hilani and noted that there is some feature much higher up and closer to 46.0B, but it is probably later, and not part of the Hilani foundation. The stones are also smaller. Perhaps this feature and our rocks are both part of a later phase or phases possibly in relation to each other.

notes.title: 08-07-17 (NSK)
notes.content: In the norteastern corner of the square is a spot with heated clay which could be older than the topsoil. Kate and I are thinking about to level the northwestern corner in order to understand their relation.

This note was lost, so what follows is not complete. We finished the pass begun yesterday, exposing more of the orange material beneath which is part of the destruction horizon. The square was also expanded to the NE by 40 cm. The remaining 10 cm is meant to preserve the grid stakes. We expanded in order to make sure we hit the foundations of the Hilani. In the middle of this strip, excavated as a separate pail, the highest hump is extremely loose as before, indicating a more recent dump event on top of the dump event from a previous excavation. Modern trash was found. L17-2005 was opened in the NE half of the square for the very rocky dump pile beneath the topsoil.

First, we finished the 3 cm pass that we began yesterday in this locus. We then decided to begin a 10 cm pass in the SW corner in order to make it more level and chase the burnt orangish material from the destruction horizon. Particularly our goal was to connect the burnt areas in the W corner and central part of the SE section. We did not finish the pass, but at the bottom, we did indeed find some of the burnt material. Some large pieces of bone and much pottery was found in this locus. There appears to be a lot of clay in the soil close to the SW baulk and S corner.

Today, we scraped this locus along the SE section in order to find more of the orangish burnt material. We were not very successful and decided not to chase the orangish material or risk creating a hole. We also finished the 10 cm pass begun yesterday around the pit, L17-2005. We found a lot of bone. There are mottled areas of orange at the bottom of the pass, causing us to open a new locus, L17-2011. We now determined that we removed all the topsoil, and this locus was finally closed.

We reopened this locus today because we noticed that a very large and very small patch of it remained on top of L17-2011 west of the center of the square and extending somewhat to the NW baulk. We removed these patches. We thought that they might have been part of a pit, but it would appear that we just missed these patches in yesterday's pass. Some modern plastic lay at the bottom of this pail (#18), beneath which is orangish soil.

We reopened this locus today in order to remove topsoil from our 4.5 m expansion to the NW. 10 cm pass with big pick. Modern material mixed in with ancient. EBA(?) figurine head and partial loom weight found. Beginning to hit orange debris in SW of locus.

Split locus up based on fact that the NE 2/3 is stony and we expect modern house foundations here, and the SW 1/3 is becoming orange indicating MB destruction debris. Consistent with what we found last year. 10 cm pass with big pick in both pails, and additional leveling passes where necessary with no pail changes.
Topsoil of SE expansion. Greyish-brown, loose dirt with pebbles, glass, plastic, other modern inclusions as well as sherds. Also some large roots.
Coming down on a burnt orange patch in the W corner of the expansion.
We opened a new sounding northern and the first layer of this new trench is this debris layer.
New pass in the new sounding. We found some plastic bags wich indicate us that the layer is mixed with modern material.
We continue to clean the north western part of the square.
We especially cleaned the north corner and the possible Iron age wall wich was visible since we opened this sounding.
